Introduction¶

Tip: In this section of the report, provide a brief introduction to the dataset you've selected for analysis. At the end of this section, describe the questions that you plan on exploring over the course of the report. Try to build your report around the analysis of at least one dependent variable and three independent variables.

If you haven't yet selected and downloaded your data, make sure you do that first before coming back here. If you're not sure what questions to ask right now, then make sure you familiarize yourself with the variables and the dataset context for ideas of what to explore.

The data comes from the FBI's National Instant Criminal Background Check System. The NICS is used by to determine whether a prospective buyer is eligible to buy firearms or explosives. Gun shops call into this system to ensure that each customer does not have a criminal record or isnt otherwise ineligible to make a purchase. The data has been supplemented with state level data from census.gov

The NICS data is found in one sheet of an .xlsx file. It contains the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type.

The U.S. census data data is found in a .csv file. It contains several variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data point per state (2016), but a few have data for more than one year

The questions that I intened to explore in my analysis:¶

Research Question 1: show the histogram for each gun type and permits¶

Research Question 2: Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?¶

Research Question 3: What is the overall trend of gun purchases?¶

Research Question 4: Compare between the total gun purchases in the five US_territories?¶

Research Question 5: Which US_territory has had the highest growth in gun registrations?¶

Research Question 6: Which state had the highest total number of guns?¶

Research Question 7: Which states have was the highest at permit recheck?¶

Research Question 8: compare between the permit, permit recheck and totals ffor each state?¶

Research Question 9: Show the different gun types destripution over the states¶

Conclusions¶

The number of permitted guns in kentucky is 24926779¶

The number of guns in kentucky is 29762434 (after using each data from each gun alone, we found that it's not the highest state but Texas is the highest one¶

Gun purchases trend increases regulary with spikes and the start of each year and it seriously spikes in 2014 and between 2016 and 2017¶

For 17 years only 'District of Columbia' and 'Virgin Islands' had any permitted guns and the later was significantly higher (11485 vs 330 in D.C.)¶

Most States doesn't have a single permit recheck, and the highes one is Illinois state¶

Limitations¶

The last diagram showed that the 'totals' column has missing data which lead to the misleading result of the state with the highest number of guns, this implies to that there are missing data in the daataset, specially the ' totals' columns, the totals column need to be updated

They didn't specify the if the 'hadgun', 'long_gun', 'other' columns include all the the other same-gun-type related columns, it's very misleading, I summed up the same-gun-type related columns be ause the analysis didn't seem like to change by much and it seemed more reasonable to sum but they needed to clarify this point
